ABUJA – Labour Unions in the nation’s petroleum sector may have shelved their proposed planned strike action following updates provided by the Nigerian National Petroleum Company (NNPC) Limited on the current status of the road construction and rehabilitation projects under the road infrastructure tax credit scheme. According to a communique jointly signed by Otunba S. A. Oladiti, National Chairman PTD, Mr. Yusuf Otthman, NARTO President, Comrade Williams Akporeha Abiodun Adeniji, NUPENG President, ED F&A, NMDPRAand Mele Kolo Kyari, Group Managing Director, NNPC Limited, assured the stakeholders (NUPENG, NARTO and PTD) that the funding earmarked for the 21 critical roads will be applied for the intended purpose only. The statement noted that to allay the fears of the stakeholders, NNPC and all parties commit to working together in the monitoring of the road projects and reviewed of freight rate for transporters. Fashola Flags Off Ember Month Rehabilitation Works, Calls For… Kyari Engages PTD, NARTO, FIRS, Others On Plans To Rebuild Roads “The stakeholders requested for completion of the ongoing discussion on the review of the freight rates to cover operational costs and highlighted the precarious situation that truck owners face in the light of current economic realities. “NMDPRA informed the meeting that a committee has been constituted to review the rates which includes PTD, NARTO and NUPENG in addition to other stakeholders. “All parties agreed to work expeditiously towards concluding the review of the freight rate and make recommendations to the Government. The Authority to advise on definite close-out date during the week of 21st February 2022. “Collaboration on ensuring Nationwide availability of petroleum products “All parties agreed to work closely to ensure efficient distribution of petroleum products across the country” reads the statement in parts.